# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iso-development-environment
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Protocol developers define data structures in ASN.1 modules, which are generally a section of a broader standards document written in the ASN.1 language.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The advantage is that the ASN.1 description of the data encoding is independent of a particular computer or programming language.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Because ASN.1 is both human-readable and machine-readable, an ASN.1 compiler can compile modules into libraries of code, codecs, that decode or encode the data structures.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Some ASN.1 compilers can produce code to encode or decode several encodings, e.g. packed, BER or XML.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] In 1988, ASN.1 moved to its own standard, **X.208**, due to wide applicability.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The substantially revised 1995 version is covered by the **X.680**–**X.683** series.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The latest revision of the X.680 series of recommendations is the 6.0 Edition, published in 2021.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] ASN.1 is a data type declaration notation.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] It does not define how to manipulate a variable of such a type.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Manipulation of variables is defined in other languages such as SDL (Specification and Description Language) for executable modeling or TTCN-3 (Testing and Test Control Notation) for conformance testing.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Both these languages natively support ASN.1 declarations.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] It is possible to import an ASN.1 module and declare a variable of any of the ASN.1 types declared in the module.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] ASN.1 is used to define a large number of protocols.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Its most extensive uses continue to be telecommunications, cryptography, and biometrics.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] ASN.1 is closely associated with a set of encoding rules that specify how to represent a data structure as a series of bytes.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Encodes elements as tag-length-value (TLV) sequences.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Typically provides several options as to how data values are to be encoded.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] This is one of the most flexible encoding rules.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Employs almost all of the same restrictions as the DER but the noteworthy difference is that the CER specify that many large values (especially strings) are to be "chopped up" into individual substring elements at the 1000-byte or 1000-character mark (depending on the data type).
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The PERs in general are capable of producing very compact encodings, but at the expense of complexity; they are also highly dependent upon constraints placed on data types.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Encodes values on bits, but if the bits encoded are not evenly divisible by eight, padding bits are added until an integral number of octets encode the value.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] A variant of the PER-U that specifies a single way of encoding values.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The CPERs have a similar relationship to the PERs that the DER and the CER have to the BER.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] A variant of the PER-A that specifies a single way of encoding values.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Variant of XER that produces only one possible encoding for a given value.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Variant of XER that adds options and instructions controlling stylistic choices of the encoder.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] A set of encoding rules that encodes values on octets, but does not encode tags or length determinants like the BER does.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Data values encoded using the OER often look like those found in "record-based" protocols.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The OER were designed to be easy to implement and to produce encodings more compact than those produced by the BER.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] In addition to reducing the effort of developing encoder/decoders, the use of OER can decrease bandwidth utilization (though not as much as the PER), save CPU cycles, and lower encoding/decoding latency.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] ITU X.696 OER is derived from a largely-compatible "OER" defined in NEMA's NTCIP 1102.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] NEMA's OER is in turn a clarified and expanded version of the unfortunately-named NEMA Packed Encoding Rules (NEMA PER).
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Variant of OER where each value only has one possible octet representation.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The ASCII-only version is canonical, i.e. each value only has one possible octet representation.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Intended to represent encoded data to the user or input data from the user, in a very straightforward format similar to the ASN.1's value notation.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] (LDAP) and is rarely used outside of it.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The use of GSER in actual protocols is discouraged since not all character string encodings supported by ASN.1 can be reproduced in it.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Customization of encoding occurs through instead of ECN.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Encodes elements as tag-length-value (TLV) sequences like the Basic Encoding Rules (BER) does.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] stack, in which code for reading and writing this format can be found.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Used primarily in telecommunications related protocols, such as GSM and SS7.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Designed to produce an identical encoding from ASN.1 that previously existing protocols not specified in ASN.1 would produce.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] detailing the "Flat Tree Light Weight Syntax" (FTLWS).
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Abandoned in 1997 due to the superior performance of the Packed Encoding Rules (PER).
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Optionally Big-Endian or Little-Endian transmission as well as 8-bit, 16-bit, and 32-bit memory words.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Meant to be as compact as possible, like the later Packed Encoding Rules (PER).
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Definition of these encoding rules were a byproduct of INRIA's work on the Flat Tree Light Weight Syntax (FTLWS).
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] ASN.1 recommendations provide a number of predefined encoding rules.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] If none of the existing encoding rules are suitable, the Encoding Control Notation (ECN, X.692) provides a way for a user to define his or her own customized encoding rules.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Privacy-Enhanced Mail (PEM) encoding is entirely unrelated to ASN.1 and its codecs, but encoded ASN.1 data, which is often binary, is often PEM-encoded so that it can be transmitted as textual data, e.g. over SMTP relays, or through copy/paste buffers.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] ASN.1 language and encoding specifications do not specify details such as what filename extension to use when a chunk of data is stored as a file on a computer.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] This could be a specification published by creators of Foo Protocol.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Conversation flows, transaction interchanges, and states are not defined in ASN.1, but are left to other notations and textual description of the protocol.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] ASN.1 supports constraints on values and sizes, and extensibility.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] This change constrains trackingNumbers to have a value between 0 and 199 inclusive, and questionNumbers to have a value between 10 and 20 inclusive.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The size of the questions array can be between 0 and 10 elements, with the answers array between 1 and 10 elements.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The anArray field is a fixed length 100 element array of integers that must be in the range 0 to 1000.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Good ASN.1 compilers will generate (in C, C++, Java, etc.) source code that will automatically check that transactions fall within these constraints.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Transactions that violate the constraints should not be accepted from, or presented to, the application.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Constraint management in this layer significantly simplifies protocol specification because the applications will be protected from constraint violations, reducing risk and cost.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The above examples only make use of syntax from X.680.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] More advanced constraints from X.682 are not used.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] To send the myQuestion message through the network, the message is serialized (encoded) as a series of bytes using one of the encoding rules.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The Foo protocol specification should explicitly name one set of encoding rules to use, so that users of the Foo protocol know which one they should use and expect.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The above is an example of X.681, specifically of the *ObjectAssignment* construct.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Alternatively, it is possible to encode the same ASN.1 data structure with XML Encoding Rules (XER) to achieve greater human readability "over the wire".
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] In this format, type tags for the required elements are not encoded, so it cannot be parsed without knowing the expected schemas used to encode.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Additionally, the bytes for the value of the IA5String are packed using 7-bit units instead of 8-bit units, because the encoder knows that encoding an IA5String byte value requires only 7 bits.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The last 6 bits in the encoded PER are padded with null bits in the 6 least significant bits of the last byte c0 : these extra bits may not be transmitted or used for encoding something else if this sequence is inserted as a part of a longer unaligned PER sequence.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] In this case, each octet is padded individually with null bits on their unused most significant bits.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] A list of tools supporting ASN.1 can be found on the ITU-T Tool web page.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] ASN.1 is similar in purpose and use to Google Protocol Buffers and Apache Thrift, which are also interface description languages for cross-platform data serialization.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Like those languages, it has a schema (in ASN.1, called a "module"), and a set of encodings, typically type–length–value encodings.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Unlike them, ASN.1 does not provide a single and readily usable open-source implementation, and is published as a specification to be implemented by third-party vendors.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] However, ASN.1, defined in 1984, predates them by many years.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] It also includes a wider variety of basic data types, some of which are obsolete, and has more options for extensibility.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] A single ASN.1 message can include data from multiple modules defined in multiple standards, even standards defined years apart.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] ASN.1 also includes built-in support for constraints on values and sizes.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] For instance, a module can specify an integer field that must be in the range 0 to 100.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The length of a sequence of values (an array) can also be specified, either as a fixed length or a range of permitted lengths.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Constraints can also be specified as logical combinations of sets of basic constraints.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Values used as constraints can either be literals used in the PDU specification, or ASN.1 values specified elsewhere in the schema file.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Some ASN.1 tools will make these ASN.1 values available to programmers in the generated source code.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Used as constants for the protocol being defined, developers can use these in the protocol's logic implementation.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Thus all the PDUs and protocol constants can be defined in the schema, and all implementations of the protocol in any supported language draw upon those values.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] This avoids the need for developers to hand code protocol constants in their implementation's source code.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] This significantly aids protocol development; the protocol's constants can be altered in the ASN.1 schema and all implementations are updated simply by recompiling, promoting a rapid and low risk development cycle.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] If the ASN.1 tools properly implement constraints checking in the generated source code, this acts to automatically validate protocol data during program operation.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Generally ASN.1 tools will include constraints checking into the generated serialization / deserialization routines, raising errors or exceptions if out-of-bounds data is encountered.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] It is complex to implement all aspects of ASN.1 constraints in an ASN.1 compiler.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Not all tools support the full range of possible constraints expressions.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] XML schema and JSON schema both support similar constraints concepts.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Microsoft's xsd.exe compiler ignores them.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Some ASN.1 tools are able to translate between ASN.1 and XML schema (XSD).
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] The translation is standardised by the ITU.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] This makes it possible for a protocol to be defined in ASN.1, and also automatically in XSD.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Thus it is possible (though perhaps ill-advised) to have in a project an XSD schema being compiled by ASN.1 tools producing source code that serializes objects to/from JSON wireformat.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] A more practical use is to permit other sub-projects to consume an XSD schema instead of an ASN.1 schema, perhaps suiting tools availability for the sub-projects language of choice, with XER used as the protocol wireformat.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] OSS Nokalva offers a tool for converting a JSON data object or a JSON schema into an ASN.1 definition.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] There is not yet a tool for generating a JSON schema describing the JER-encoded structure of an ASN.1 data structure.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] OSS Nokalva also offers a tool for converting a Protocol Buffers schema into an ASN.1 definition.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] Many programming languages define language-specific serialization formats.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] For instance, Python's "pickle" module and Ruby's "Marshal" module.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] They are generally language-specific, which makes them easier to use in ad hoc storage scenarios, but inappropriate for communications protocols.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] JSON and XML similarly do not require a schema, making them easy to use.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] They are also both cross-platform standards that are broadly popular for communications protocols, particularly when combined with a JSON schema or XML schema.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] ASN.1 is visually similar to Augmented Backus-Naur form (ABNF), which is used to define many Internet protocols like HTTP and SMTP.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] However, in practice they are quite different: ASN.1 defines a data structure, which can be encoded in various ways (e.g.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] ABNF, on the other hand, defines the encoding ("syntax") at the same time it defines the data structure ("semantics").
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] ABNF tends to be used more frequently for defining textual, human-readable protocols, and generally is not used to define type–length–value encodings.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] ASN.1 is also visually similar to CSN.1.
[src:iso-development-environment/abstract-syntax-notation-one] However, CSN.1 also defines the encoding of an object, specifically on the bit level.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:iso-development-environment/american-national-standards-institute] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] An **application layer** is an abstraction layer that specifies the shared communication protocols and interface methods used by hosts in a communications network.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] An *application layer* abstraction is specified in both the Internet Protocol Suite (TCP/IP) and the OSI model.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] Although both models use the same term for their respective highest-level layer, the detailed definitions and purposes are different.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] The concept of the application layer emerged from early efforts to standardize network communication by defining distinct layers of protocol functionality.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] In the OSI model developed in the late 1970s and early 1980s, the application layer was explicitly separated from lower layers like session and presentation to modularize network services and applications for interoperability and clarity.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] Contrasting this, the TCP/IP model, whose origins date back to the 1970s and which became the foundation of the modern Internet, integrates these functions into a broader application layer that handles process-to-process communication.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] This design emphasizes simplicity and robustness by placing intelligence and complexity on the network's edge rather than the core, enabling nearly any network to interconnect.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] As a result, the application layer serves as the interface for diverse networking protocols that drive everyday Internet-based services, reflecting decades of evolution aimed at flexible, interoperable communication across heterogeneous networks.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] In the Internet protocol suite, the application layer contains the communications protocols and interface methods used in process-to-process communications across an Internet Protocol (IP) computer network.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] The application layer only standardizes communication and depends upon the underlying transport layer protocols to establish host-to-host data transfer channels and manage the data exchange in a client–server or peer-to-peer networking model.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] Though the TCP/IP application layer does not describe specific rules or data formats that applications must consider when communicating, the original specification (in RFC 1123) does rely on and recommend the robustness principle for application design.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] In the OSI model, the definition of the application layer is narrower in scope.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] The OSI model defines the application layer as only the interface responsible for communicating with host-based and user-facing applications.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] OSI then explicitly distinguishes the functionality of two additional layers, the session layer and presentation layer, as separate levels below the application layer and above the transport layer.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] OSI specifies a strict modular separation of functionality at these layers and provides protocol implementations for each.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] In contrast, the Internet Protocol Suite compiles these functions into a single layer.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] Originally, the OSI model consisted of two kinds of application layer services with their related protocols.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] These two sublayers are the common application service element (CASE) and specific application service element (SASE).
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] Generally, an application layer protocol is realized by using the functionality of several application service elements.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] Some application service elements invoke different procedures based on the version of the session service available.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] The common application service element sublayer provides services for the application layer and requests services from the session layer.
[src:iso-development-environment/application-layer] The IETF definition document for the application layer in the Internet Protocol Suite is RFC 1123.
[src:iso-development-environment/asc-x9] The **Accredited Standards Committee X9** (ASC X9, Inc.) is an ANSI (American National Standards Institute) accredited standards developing organization, responsible for developing voluntary open consensus standards for the financial services industry in the U.S.
[src:iso-development-environment/asc-x9] Membership in ASC X9 is open to all U.S. domiciled companies and organizations in the financial services industry.
[src:iso-development-environment/asc-x9] The committee was founded in 1974 under the American National Standards Institute, to develop financial industry standards following a surge in electronic banking, automated clearing, and data security needs.
[src:iso-development-environment/asc-x9] In 1984 it played a major role role in supporting the Check Clearing for the 21st Century Act (Check 21) through development of check image exchange and related standards.
[src:iso-development-environment/asc-x9] In the 1990s it expanded its cryptography standards, developing foundational specifications for secure data exchange and public key infrastructures (e.g., X9.42, X9.73, X9.24).
[src:iso-development-environment/asc-x9] In 2001, the organization was incorporated as ASC X9, Inc., transitioning from a pure ANSI committee to a non-profit industry consortium still accredited by ANSI.
[src:iso-development-environment/asc-x9] During the 2000s and 2010s it joined with international bodies like ISO/TC 68, helping shape ISO 20022 and other global standards for payments and securities messaging.
[src:iso-development-environment/asc-x9] The Accredited Standards Committee X9 develops, establishes, maintains, and promotes standards for the Financial Services Industry in the United States in order to facilitate delivery of financial services and products.
[src:iso-development-environment/austrian-standards-international] The first standard was published in 1921 on metric screw threads.
[src:iso-development-environment/austrian-standards-international] In 1932, the committee's name was shortened to the *Österreichischer Normenausschuss* (Austrian Standards Committee).
[src:iso-development-environment/austrian-standards-international] With the Austrian *Anschluss* to Nazi Germany in 1938, it became a branch office of the German *Deutsches Institut für Normung* (DIN) standards organization, but resumed operations in its own right after World War II, and was a founding ISO member in 1946.
[src:iso-development-environment/austrian-standards-international] The 1954 Federal Act on Standardization recognized the activities of the committee, and the Act, as amended, serves as its legal basis.
[src:iso-development-environment/austrian-standards-international] The Austrian Standards Committee's name was changed to *ON Österreichisches Normungsinstitut* in 1969.
[src:iso-development-environment/austrian-standards-international] On 1 March 2006, the Institute published ON rule ONR 168000, used to calculate the monetary value of a brand.
[src:iso-development-environment/austrian-standards-international] In 2018, the name was changed to Austrian Standards International.
[src:iso-development-environment/austrian-standards-international] The Institute is located at Heinestrasse 38, 1020 Vienna.
[src:iso-development-environment/austrian-standards-international] The acronym ÖNORM designates a national standard published by the Austrian Standards International and applicable to Austria alone.
[src:iso-development-environment/austrian-standards-international] Austrian national standards have the acronym "ÖNORM" followed by one letter and a unique number.
[src:iso-development-environment/austrian-standards-international] In the examples above, the letter "S" following "ÖNORM" indicates that these standards address topics not covered elsewhere (*Sonstige Normengebiete* in German).
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The **National Standardization Agency** of Indonesia (Indonesian: *Badan Standardisasi Nasional*; **BSN**) is the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) member body for Indonesia.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] BSN is a non-ministerial Indonesian government agency with the main task of carrying out governmental tasks in the field of standardization and conformity assessment in Indonesia.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The agency is also responsible to develop and maintain the Indonesian National Standard.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Actively involved in various International Organizations such as ISO, IEC, CAC, APEC, APLAC, ILAC, PAC, ASEAN, and so on.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Active participation of BSN can be in the form of attending international standard formulation sessions in order to fight for the interests of Indonesia, as well as hosting the session / hosting.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Encouraging the central government, regional governments, associations, industry, and universities to participate actively in developing and promoting SNI.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The efforts of BSN to encourage stakeholders to jointly conduct standardization and conformity assessment activities, are formally formulated through the signing of the Cooperation Text (MOU).
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Conducting research and testing of SNI products in the market, of which the results can be inputs for relevant Ministries that have the capacity to be market supervisors.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The research activities conducted by BSN can also be included for SNI development and maintenance activities.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Organizing National Standards of Measurement Unit that enable metrological activities in Indonesia to be recognized by the world.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Implementation of guidance and general administrative services in the fields of general planning, administration, organization and governance, staffing, finance, filing, coding, equipment and household.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 5. organizing education and training in its fields.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The establishment of BSN is closely related to the long history of standardization in Indonesia.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The development and application of standards began during the Dutch and Japanese colonial periods and continued after Indonesia declared independence and became officially sovereign.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Standardization was initially used to support colonial economic activities and ensure their smooth operation.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Dutch engineers, who were mostly civil engineers, began to set standards for building materials, transportation equipment, and electrical installation standards, as well as requirements for external lines.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] During World War II and the Japanese occupation (1942-1945), formal standardization activities were halted.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] However, on August 17, 1945, Indonesia proclaimed its independence.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The country immediately formed a government and planned for development to improve the standard of living and welfare of the people, with the goal of achieving equality with other countries.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1951 the amendment to the "Raad Normalization" statute was formed and the Indonesian Normalization Fund Foundation (YDNI) was formed.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1955 YDNI represented Indonesia as a member of the ISO international standards organization and in 1966 YDNI successfully represented Indonesia as a member of the International Electrotechnical Commission / IEC.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] It turns out that this law has not been able to be a means of managing overall standardization activities.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The government began to place standardization as a strategic function in supporting national development.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1973, the "National System Development for Standardization" program was established as a priority.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1976, the National Standardization System Preparation Committee was formed.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1984, with the Decree of the President of the Republic of Indonesia the National Standardization Board (DSN) was formed with the main task of establishing standardization policies, coordinating and fostering cooperation in the field of national standardization.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The Chairperson of the National Standardization Board is held by the State Minister for Research and Technology, Prof.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Through the struggle of the previous leadership, Alm.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Herudi Kartowisastro, on March 27, 1997, the government dissolved the DSN which subsequently changed to the National Standardization Body.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] BSN itself is a Non-Ministry Government Institution (LPNK) that is given the task by the government to foster and coordinate all standardization and conformity assessment activities in Indonesia.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The establishment of BSN was based on Presidential Decree No.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 13 of 1997 perfected by Presidential Decree No.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 166 of 2000 concerning Position, Duties, Functions, Authority, Organizational Structure and Work Procedures of Non-Departmental Government Institutions as amended several times, and the most recent by Presidential Decree No.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 4 of 2018, concerning the National Standardization Agency.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In order to enhance the development of the Indonesian National Standard (SNI), the government established Government Regulation No.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 102 of 2000 concerning National Standardization.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 20 of 2014 concerning Standardization and Conformity Assessment was stipulated.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] With the existence of this Law, the government will further strengthen the existence and role of BSN in the development process in Indonesia both in the context of physical development, efficient management of natural resources, and the development of highly competitive Indonesian people.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Welcoming the era of globalization which demands high competitiveness, as well as the implementation of Law No.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 20 of 2014, the BSN successfully reorganized itself to include a new structure namely the Deputy for the National Standard Measuring Unit (SNSU) in 2018.
[src:iso-development-environment/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The chairman of BSN is under and directly responsible to the President of Indonesia.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] The **British Standards Institution** (**BSI**) is the national standards body of the United Kingdom.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] BSI produces technical standards on a wide range of products and services and also supplies standards certification services for business and personnel.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] BSI was founded as the Engineering Standards Committee in London in 1901.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] It subsequently extended its standardization work and became the British Engineering Standards Association in 1918, adopting the name British Standards Institution in 1931 after receiving a Royal Charter in 1929.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] In 1998, a revision of the Charter enabled the organization to diversify and acquire other businesses, and the trading name was changed to BSI Group.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] The Group now operates in 195 countries.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] The core business remains standards and standards related services, although the majority of the Group's revenue comes from management systems assessment and certification work.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] In 2021, BSI appointed its first female chief executive officer, Susan Taylor Martin.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] BSI produces British Standards, and, as the UK's National Standards Body, is also responsible for the UK publication, in English, of international and European standards.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] BSI is obliged to adopt and publish all European Standards as identical British Standards (prefixed BS EN) and to withdraw pre-existing British Standards that are in conflict.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] However, it has the option to adopt and publish international standards (prefixed BS ISO or BS IEC).
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] In response to commercial demands, BSI also produces commissioned standards products such as Publicly Available Specifications (PASs), Private Standards and Business Information Publications.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] These products are commissioned by individual organizations and trade associations to meet their needs for standardized specifications, guidelines, codes of practice etc.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] Because they are not subject to the same consultation and consensus requirements as formal standards, the lead time is shorter.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] BSI also publishes standards-related books, CD-ROMs, subscription and web-based products as well as providing training on standards-related issues.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] With 80,000 clients, BSI is one of the world's largest certification bodies.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] It audits and provides certification to companies worldwide who implement management systems standards.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] BSI also runs training courses that cover the implementation and auditing requirements of national and international management systems standards.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] BSI's best known product in the UK is the Kitemark, a registered certification mark first used in 1903.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] The Kitemark – which is recognized by 82% of UK adults – signifies products or services which have been assessed and tested as meeting the requirements of the related specification or standard within a Kitemark scheme.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] BSI also conducts testing of products for a range of certifications, including for CE marking.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] CE marking must be applied to a wide range of products intended for sale in the European Economic Area.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] Frequently, manufacturers or importers need a third-party certification of their product from an accredited or 'Notified' body.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] BSI holds Notified Body status for 15 EU Directives, including construction products, marine equipment, pressurized equipment and personal protective equipment.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] BSI also conducts testing for manufacturers developing new products and has facilities to test across a wide range of sectors, including construction, fire safety, electrical and electronic and engineering products.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] BSI provides regulatory and quality management reviews and product certification for medical device manufacturers in the Worldwide.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] It is the market leader in the US, the world's biggest healthcare market.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] In 2021, BSI Group, with support from the Construction Products Association, led the development of a product identification and traceability system known as *BSI Identify*.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] The initiative responded to recommendations made by Dame Judith Hackitt following her review of building safety, which called for wider adoption of permanent product marking and consistent labelling systems to improve traceability across the built environment sector.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] BSI Identify uses new Digital Object Identifier (DOI) technology "to deliver a unique, constant, and interoperable identifier", known as a BSI UPIN, "which can be assigned to products to help UK manufacturers to directly manage information about their products in the supply chain".
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] The aim of the BSI Identify programme is that "wherever you are with [a] product, you can take a snapshot of the QR code with your mobile device, and it will immediately take you to the product technical data sheet.
[src:iso-development-environment/bsi-group] The BSI coat of arms was granted by the College of Arms in 1951.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] The ISODE software was initially a public domain / open source implementation, led by Marshall Rose.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] Following version 6.0, Marshall handed the lead over to Colin Robbins and Julian Onions, who coordinated the 7.0 and 8.0 releases.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] Version 8.0 was the final public domain release, made on June 19, 1992.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] The Open Source version is still available, even if only for historic interest.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] The software was ported to a wide set of Unix and Linux variants.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] The ISODE stack was an implementation of layers 3 to 6 of the OSI model.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] The stack also implemented an ASN.1 compiler.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] The ISODE Stack was the basis for a number of OSI applications.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] ISODE formed the basis an implementation for the X.400 email protocol, called PP.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] PP included a fully operational SMTP/MIME email server and an X.400/SMTP Mixer gateway.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] PP also implemented a P7 Messagestore (PPMS).
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] PP was designed by Steve Kille and the lead engineer was Julian Onions.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] ISODE had a full X.500 and LDAP directory called QUIPU (*incorrectly* pronounced kwip-ooo by the project).
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] Quipu implemented a DSA and a Directory User Agent (DUA) called DISH.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] X.500 was considered too heavyweight to access directories, Colin Robbins implemented a proprietary protocol to solve the problem, this was then significantly re-worked by Tim Howes for DIXIE which led to the development of the Lightweight Directory Access Protocol.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] QUIPU was designed by Kille and the lead engineer was Robbins, largely funded by the INCA project, and used extensively in the Paradise academic X.500 directory pilot.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] ISODE contained and implementation of FTAM, and implemented an FTAM-FTP gateway.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] ISODE contained a virtual terminal (VT) implementation and a VT-Telnet gateway.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] ISODE has a full implementation of a PKI Certificate Authority built on top of it by the OSISEC project.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] OSISEC was developed by Mike Roe & Peter Williams and integrated into ISODE by Robbins.
[src:iso-development-environment/iso-development-environment] ISODE has a full implementation of a CMIP/TMN built on top of it by the OSIMIS project.
